exes by income, both at the individual and household level, as well as by other dimensions of stratification, such as education, occupational status, and migration status. Our results indicate high fluctuations in spatial segregation levels among the different dimensions of social stratification, and similar levels among the three cities. The spatial mismatch by income is high and significantly increases over time, both at the individual and household level. These results suggest that social inequality in Mexican cities has been exacerbated by the increase in geographical barriers between advantaged and poor strata, thus increasing the risk of pervasive social problems associated to the residential segregation of the poor.},
author = {Ariza, Marina and Sol{\'{i}}s, Patricio},
