@article{Ruebeck2024,
   abstract = {Minority-group workers in the US understand that discrimination is widespread, and when they experience rejection at work, observe incomplete information about the cause. Whether accurate or not, perceived discrimination may generate distrust, retaliation, or anticipated further discrimination. It is therefore important to assess how workers form beliefs about experiencing discrimination and how those beliefs affect job performance and labor supply. In an online experiment (N≈5000), I randomly assign workers to be evaluated by promotion procedures with varied potential to discriminate and the information workers have about past promotions. When rejected job candidates learn that previously-promoted workers are primarily white men, many infer bias even when they know that hiring managers (or algorithms) did not know race and gender. These perceptions have important consequences: learning that a manager knew workers' race and gender and previously promoted mostly white men increases the share of workers who perceive discrimination from 1 to 31 percent, lowers retention by 3-6 percent, and increases reservation wages by 9 percent. My findings suggest that employers could shrink retention gaps and boost performance by reducing perceived discrimination, but that objectively neutral procedures are unlikely to alone eradicate perceptions of discrimination when minority groups remain under-represented.},
